title: For Sale:   WWII Training Round/Shell with WINCHESTER Advertising
postcontent: I have WWII Training Round/Shell with WINCHESTER Advertising. These are a MUST HAVE for any Winchester or WWII buff. These have never been used and were found in a storage shed where they had been sitting for quite some time. The shells are made of wood, metal and brass. I was told these rounds/shells were used for training and the weight of these are the same as an original shell. They are 30" long and weigh approximately 28 pounds. Most are marked MK V 3" 50cal training rounds most commonly mounted on Navy escorts and submarines. The Winchester printing was likely a post war addition but is well done, and appears to have aged consistently with the rest of the piece. My educated guess is they were stamped and used Winchester promotional material shortly after the end of the war.

title: For Sale:  Kel Tec KSG with Aimpoint PRO
postcontent:
I have a Kel Tec KSG.  It is about 9 months old and I have have put less then 100 rounds through it.  I love the gun and I am in no need to sell it.  I took the Aimpoint Pro off my new Daniel Defense DDM4 as I wanted a longer range scope on there.  I have hung the PRO on the KSG but have not taken it out to sight it in.  Great scope for the KSG.  

If you know what a KSG is then you are already ahead of the curve.   I have not taken pictures of it yet with the PRO on it so I am not going to post pictures at this point.  Anyone serious we can work something out.  The KSG has a manufacturers price tag of $1197 (used to be $880) and I bought it new in the box with Magpul MBUS sights, a fore-grip (no longer with it) and sling for $1100. I see some people were able to find some below MSRP but that was rare, especially for the updated ones.  If you want to know the difference check out You Tube.  When you watch the videos you will see where people were having FF and FE problems.  I must admit that worried me and when I got mine I bought several different boxes of ammo to try.  I had some low end Federals that would expand the empty casing and stick in the chamber which happened to be the ones I tried first.  I switched over to Winchester Loads and have used slugs, PDX rounds, buckshot, and bird shot with no issues at all.

I figured eventually they would go down in price but that has not happened yet in fact they are going up. As you can see from checking further on Armslist the price has gone up. And in the stores I think they are still hard to find.  But I haven't looked all that hard.  But what I do have is a gun that I spent money on and I am not opposed to making money and replacing the shotgun at a later date.  I bought this gun as a SHTF defense weapon to augment my longer reach stuff.  At 15 rounds (or 29 with mini shells) it is perfect for that job and once the Aimpoint is sighted it is a bad ass tool. 

So no need to send me emails telling me I am whacked for asking that much because it is just a number.  The value is to the guy who wants that shotgun.  As I said I do not need to sell it and not all that convinced I want to sell it but would be a fool not to accept that kind of return on my investment.

title: For Sale:  NIB Kahr Arms P380 w/Crimson Trace
postcontent:
I have a brand new Kahr P380 with Crimson Trace trigger guard laser. The P380 pistol from Kahr, chambered for the .380 ACP caliber, has a 2.53" barrel and an overall length of 4.9", with a height of only 3.9". It weighs in at just under 10 ounces (9.97 to be exact) without a magazine. The P380 is constructed of a black polymer frame, matte stainless slide, and textured polymer grips. The black polymer frame features 4140 steel inserts molded into the frame in the front and back for added rigidity and strength not found on competitive brands. The P380 features a lock breech, modified Browning type recoil lug, Kahr's six patents including the "safe cam" action found in all Kahr pistols. These features result in a micro-compact pistol in a fighting caliber with very little felt recoil and quick follow-up shots. The P380 does not have a magazine disconnect nor does it have "double-strike" capability. The P380 also boasts "real" sights, featuring drift adjustable, white bar-dot combat sights that dovetail into the slide, with optional night sights available.

The quality of the tiny P380 from Kahr is unrivaled when compared to competitive brands. The barrel is a premium Lothar Walther match grade polygonal rifled design, allowing higher muzzle velocities for hollow point ammo than other conventional rifled barrels on competitive brands. The .75" slide is machined from solid 416R stainless bar stock and locks back on the last round. The P380 model features two high quality 400 series stainless steel 6 round magazines, standard with each gun shipped. In addition, the P380 utilizes an all metal magazine catch in the polymer frame to mate with the stainless steel magazine. The magazines are USA made and are plasma welded, tumbled to remove burrs, and feature Wolff Gunsprings.

The P380 is substantially smaller than Kahr's popular PM9, and proves itself to be an ideal concealed carry weapon. Its light weight and small size, combined with Kahr's reputation for reliability, makes it the perfect pocket pistol. The P380 model is also a strong consideration as a backup gun for law enforcement. The easy to use sights are just an added bonus to this already desired pistol.
